  "formatedtext": "Hildegrim of Ch\u00e2lons -  Hildegrim of Ch\u00e2lons From , the free encyclopedia (Redirected from Hildegrin ) Jump to navigation Jump to search Hildegrim [1] ( c. 750 \u2013 19 June 827) was Bishop of Ch\u00e2lons from 804 to 810 and second abbot of Werden Abbey , after his elder brother Ludger , from 809 until his death. Life [ edit ] Like his brother Ludger, Hildegrim was of Christian Frisian noble descent. He presumably stayed at the Benedictine abbey of Monte Cassino and received a thorough liberal arts education at the Utrecht Cathedral School, founded by Bishop Gregory , and in York under Alcuin . Mentioned as deacon in 793, he was ordained a priest three years later. About 804 he became Bishop of Ch\u00e2lons. Upon Ludger's death in 809, he succeeded him as Abbot of Werden and Helmstedt in 809. [2] He is also traditionally named as the first Bishop of Halberstadt , a position now discounted by scholars; [3] nevertheless, Hildegrim is known to have been active in spreading Christianity as a missionary into the Osterwieck and Halberstadt region after the Saxon Wars of Charlemagne . Hildegrim is buried in the crypt of Werden Abbey church. He is a Catholic and Orthodox [4] saint, remembered on June 19. [5] Notes [ edit ] ^ Also Hildegrin, Hildigrin, Hildegrimus, Hildigrimus. ^ Imperial Bishops: H-P Archived January 4, 2008, at the Wayback Machine ^ Schaff, Philip. The New Schaff-Herzog Encyclopedia of Religious Knowledge . page 119 , page 505 . ^ Latin Saints of the Orthodox Patriarchate of Rome ^ \"June 19\" . Saint of the Day . St. Patricks's Catholic Church. External links [ edit ] (in German) Heiligenlexikon page (in French) Vignoble, Vall\u00e9e de la Marne Retrieved from \" https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Hildegrim_of_Ch\u00e2lons&oldid=933707641 \" Categories : 827 deaths German Benedictines Bishops of Ch\u00e2lons-sur-Marne Roman Catholic bishops of Halberstadt Medieval Dutch saints 9th-century bishops Hidden categories: W